of social and personal transformation within the pursuit of dignity, security, and mobility. Her vivid ethnography of both migrants and their South Korean advocates illuminates how social inequalities of gender, race, class, and nation operate in defining citizenship. Decentering Citizenship argues that citizenship emerges from negotiations about rights and belonging between South Koreans and migrants. As the promise of equal rights and full membership in a polity erodes in the face of global inequalities, this decentering illuminates important contestation at the margins of citizenship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCitizenshipzKorea (South) 0aForeign workers, FilipinoxCivil rightszKorea (South) 0aForeign workers, FilipinozKorea (South)xSocial conditions. 0aWomen foreign workersxCivil rightszKorea (South) 0aWomen foreign workerszKorea (South)xSocial conditions. 4aSouth Korea. 4acitizenship. 4agender. 4aglobalization. 4alabor. 4amigration. 4arights. 4athe Philippines. 4atrafficking. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479960740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804799607423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804799607.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles